# Unity Performance Optimization Guidelines

## Object Pooling
- Use **object pooling** for frequently instantiated/destroyed objects (bullets, particles, enemies)
- Implement pool managers for different object types
- Pre-allocate objects during scene loading or game initialization
- Return objects to pool instead of destroying them

## Rendering Optimization
- **Batch draw calls** by using shared materials and textures
- Use **sprite atlases** for UI elements and 2D sprites
- Implement **LOD (Level of Detail)** systems for complex 3D models
- Use **occlusion culling** for large scenes
- Minimize **overdraw** by organizing transparent objects properly

## Physics Optimization
- Use **simplified collision meshes** for complex objects
- Adjust **fixed timestep** settings for optimal physics performance
- Use **trigger colliders** instead of physics colliders when possible
- Implement **spatial partitioning** for large numbers of physics objects
- Use **physics layers** to limit unnecessary collision checks

## Memory Management
- **Cache component references** in Start() or Awake() instead of GetComponent() in Update()
- Use **object pooling** to avoid garbage collection spikes
- Minimize **string allocations** in performance-critical code
- Use **structs** for small, frequently accessed data
- Implement **proper disposal** of resources (textures, audio clips)

## CPU Optimization
- Use Unity's **Job System** for CPU-intensive operations
- Leverage **Burst Compiler** for mathematical operations
- **Profile your code** using Unity Profiler to identify bottlenecks
- Use **coroutines** instead of Update() for time-based operations
- Implement **frame rate limiting** for consistent performance

## Asset Management
- Use **asset bundles** for efficient resource loading
- Implement **asynchronous loading** for large assets
- **Compress textures** appropriately for target platforms
- Use **mipmaps** for 3D textures
- Implement **texture streaming** for large textures

## Code Optimization
- Avoid **GetComponent()** calls in Update() loops
- Use **local variables** instead of repeated property access
- Implement **early returns** to avoid unnecessary processing
- Use **object pooling** for temporary objects
- **Profile before optimizing** - measure first, optimize second 
